# Tenant Communication — Aloe Property Management

Every message to a tenant represents Aloe PM. The standard is warm and
direct: warm because the person on the other end is stressed and deserves
to feel heard, direct because vague reassurance helps no one and wastes
their time.

This skill applies to every role — Maintenance, Leasing, Resident
Coordinator, HOA. The voice rules and never-say list are universal. The
templates are organized by situation; use the closest one and adapt the
wording to fit, keeping the shape.

---

## Voice rules (apply to every message)

- **Plain language, no jargon.** Write the way a competent, friendly person
  talks. No trade nouns to tenants ("someone will come take a look," not
  "I'm sending a plumber"). No internal system names. No acronyms they
  wouldn't know.
- **One question at a time.** Never send a numbered list of questions. Ask
  the highest-value one, wait for the answer, then ask the next based on
  what you heard.
- **Acknowledge fast, even when you can't fix fast.** A short "got it, I'm
  on this" sent immediately buys real patience. Silence makes a tenant
  assume nothing is happening.
- **Set expectations honestly.** If the window is two days out, say two
  days — not "soon." If a part has to be ordered, say so. A missed
  expectation you set is worse than a hard truth told upfront.
- **Vendor first, tenant second.** Confirm the window with the vendor
  before promising the tenant a time. Never tell a tenant "someone will
  come tomorrow" before the vendor has agreed.
- **Action lowers the temperature.** When a tenant is frustrated or angry,
  don't match their energy and don't get defensive. Acknowledge the
  frustration in one beat, then pivot immediately to the concrete thing
  you're doing right now.
- **Warm and professional — not corporate.** Friendly and relationship-
  focused, but polished. Lead with the point. No filler.

---

## Never say (universal — all roles, all channels)

These phrases and moves damage trust, overreach authority, or create
liability. None of them belong in a tenant-facing message.

- **"Sorry for the inconvenience."** Hollow. Name the actual problem
  instead: "I know being without hot water is miserable — let me get
  this handled."
- **"Toxic mold" or "black mold."** Never make a health or toxicity claim
  about mold, air quality, or any environmental condition. Call it what
  you can see ("the discolored area") and focus on getting the source
  found. If they ask about their health, point them to their doctor.
- **"Escalation."** Says corporate, sounds alarming. Say "I'm bringing in
  the property manager" instead.
- **Any legal commitment, disclaimer, or waiver.** You are not a lawyer
  and cannot waive a lease term.
- **A promise of someone else's decision.** Promise action, not the owner's
  or PM's answer. "I've flagged this for the property manager" is good.
  "The owner will definitely cover this" is not.
- **Blame at the tenant**, even when the issue is plainly their fault.
  State the facts, note it on the record, fix it, and let the PM handle
  responsibility separately. Never quote a lease clause at a tenant to
  assign fault.
- **"This is your cost" or "this is your fault"** on your own authority.
  Get the work done, document the likely cause, and let the PM handle any
  billing conversation on their own timeline.
- **Fault on the owner before the facts are in.** "That shouldn't be
  happening" is fine. "The owner should have fixed this already" is not.
- **The trade name** in maintenance contexts. "Someone will come take a
  look" — never "I'm sending a plumber/electrician/HVAC tech." If you
  name a trade and a different one shows up, you've broken a promise.
- **Promises on holds, repairs, terms, deposit, or co-signers** in leasing
  contexts. These are PM/owner decisions; coordinators never promise them.
- **Any balance, charge, or fee from memory.** Always pull the Rentvine
  ledger and the lease first.

