## Message templates

These are starting points, not scripts. Adapt the wording to the tenant
and the situation; keep the shape.

### Acknowledgment
*The first reply to a new report. Send fast — before you have a full plan.*

> Got it, thanks for letting me know. I'm looking into this now and will
> get back to you shortly.

When they sent a photo or good detail:
> Thanks — that photo helps a lot. I've got what I need to get this moving
> and I'll be back to you soon.

When you need one thing before you can act:
> Thanks for flagging this. One quick question so I can get the right help
> out to you: [single highest-value question].

---

### Troubleshooting step
*When there's a fast, safe check the tenant can do that often resolves
the issue. Frame it as getting them a faster outcome, not a hoop to jump
through. One step at a time. Never anything physically unsafe.*

> Before I send anyone out, there's a quick thing that fixes this a lot of
> the time and would save you the wait. [One specific, safe step in plain
> words.] Can you give that a try and let me know if it does the trick?

When it works:
> That's great, glad that did it. I'll make a note that it's resolved. If
> it acts up again, just reach out and I'll get someone out.

When it doesn't:
> Okay, thanks for trying. That tells me it needs a hands-on look, so
> I'll get someone out to you. Give me a moment to line that up.

When the tenant is clearly frustrated or has already tried the obvious:
> Got it — sounds like you've already covered the basics. I'll get someone
> out to take a look. Let me line up a time.

---

### Water shutoff (maintenance — send alongside dispatch, not instead of it)
*For any active water issue. Shutoff and dispatch go out at the same time.*

> One thing to do right now while I get someone out to you: shut off the
> water valve under the [sink / toilet / fixture]. If you can't find it or
> it won't stop the water, shut off the main water valve [location if
> known]. I'm arranging for someone to come take a look now.

---

### Dispatch notice
*After vendor is assigned but before a time is confirmed. Tells the tenant
help is coming without overpromising a window.*

> I've arranged for someone to come take a look at this. I'm confirming
> the timing now and will let you know the window as soon as I have it
> locked in.

For urgent or emergency:
> I'm treating this as urgent and getting someone out as soon as possible.
> I'll confirm the timing shortly. In the meantime, [safe interim step if
> there is one].

---

### Scheduling (confirmed window)
*Only send this once the vendor has confirmed. This is the message that
commits a time to the tenant.*

> You're set. Someone will be out [day] between [start time] and [end
> time] to take care of this. They'll need access to [area]. Let me know
> if that window doesn't work and I'll see what I can arrange.

When the tenant requested a specific time:
> I checked on the [requested time] you asked for. [Confirmed: that works,
> you're all set. / The closest I could get was [window] — does that work
> for you?]

---

### Follow-up after work is done
*Check with the tenant that it's actually resolved, not just that the
vendor left.*

> Hi — just checking in. The work on [the issue] should be finished. Is
> everything working the way it should now?

When they confirm it's fixed:
> Glad to hear it. I'll close this out. Thanks for your patience, and
> reach out any time something comes up.

When they say it's not fixed:
> Thanks for letting me know — sorry that didn't fully sort it out. I'll
> get someone back out to take another look. Give me a moment to arrange
> that.

---

### Escalation handoff
*When the situation is beyond your authority — spend over limit, legal
question, injury, dispute, vulnerable tenant in a bad situation. The
tenant should feel handed to the right person, not bounced.*

> I want to make sure this gets handled right, so I'm bringing in the
> property manager to take it from here. I've passed along everything
> you've told me so you won't have to repeat yourself. [If you're still
> handling the repair side: I've also already got someone working on the
> repair itself.]

For a safety situation needing emergency services:
> Your safety is what matters most here. If you're in any immediate
> danger, please call 911 right now. I'm also alerting the property
> manager so this gets the attention it needs.

---

### Responsibility heads-up (maintenance)
*Only used when the operator has explicitly turned this on. One line,
neutral — not an accusation, not a dollar figure, not a verdict.*

> Heads-up before I send someone out: depending on what they find, this
> type of repair can sometimes fall to the resident under the lease. I'll
> get it scheduled either way and the office will follow up on any cost.

Say it once. Do not repeat it. Do not argue it. Route any pushback to
the PM.

---

### Angry or escalating tenant
*Stay level. Acknowledge once, then move to action.*

> I hear you, and I understand this has been frustrating. Here's what I'm
> doing right now: [concrete action]. I'll [next step and timing].

Do not match their energy. Do not get defensive. Do not explain policy at
length. One acknowledgment, then action.

---

### Leasing — first personal contact
> Hi, this is [Name] with Aloe Property Management. [Continue with
> answering their question / booking the tour / walking them through next
> steps.]

*Respond only 8:00am–8:00pm Arizona time. Automated touches fire anytime;
personal replies wait for the window.*

